description.text:
Here comes the "Flying Peach Microswift Evolution" based on my earlier project "Flying Peach", 130mm frame from MyRcMart.com, 1407 brushless motors, 3inch props, Piko BLX, Runcam Microswift or Sparrow and Eachine VTX 03.

The pod of this little beast was redesigned to be printed in flex material and to fit the new fantastic Runcam Microswift or Sparrow camera with a 35° view angle.

See by yourself how fun this little quad seems to be...

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6ewJnsJ25VI

The pod requires to be printed in flex material so the camera and Vtx can fit in without any problem, this provides also a much better protection against crashes.

As the frame was designed for 30.5-30.5 flight controller, please use the provided "Support_Piko_BLX" printed in TPU or other flex material to mount the 20-20 flight controller and help with vibrations.

title: Nimble and V6 mount for Creality CR-10

description.text:
Complex mount to mount the Nimble extruder and a E3D V6 hot end on the Creality CR-10.
This is based on the work done by Chito on this thing: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2494642

There are various fan mounts, including a mount to use the Berd-Air system. There are two sensor options, a BL Touch and a Ezable. If you need more sensors, drop me a line.

The mount is attached to the carriage plate using the 2 mount points and a screw that slides into the threaded hole in the plate. The screw needed is a M3x6 and can be tightened through the mount body.
If you have any issues or comments on this thing, feel free to contact me.

Edit2: Careful, the Fang style cooler probably will not fit. It will hit the cross bar at the top.

Edit: What is this fascination with fang style coolers in the CR-10 community?
Anyway, you asked, we promised and as promised, delivered. Only caveat here, I have not printed this thing out, so test at your own "risk"
I have added a fang style cooler and a special V6 clamp and it now also holds the 40x40 fan for the V6 and the ducting to guide it to the heat-sink. I thought it would be better to split the forces between the fang and the clamp.
To mount, install the Mount, Slide the Fang down into the grooves on the side and tighten the bolts through the Fang lightly. Then mount the V6, Clamp and the Nimble. Adjust the height of the Fang and tighten the 2 bolts. Mount the fan on top and mount the Hot end fan last. There is a little loop to tie-wrap the fan cable to the Clamp. Check the Fang height again and you are done.

The STL models are checked and optimised. The parts that need a different orientation to print properly are rotated to the preferred printing position.

The Nimble Extruder

With an installed weight of less than 27 grams on your carriage/effector the Zesty Nimble is smallest and lightest extruder you can buy, it has ample torque and can be mounted in multiple orientations.

The Nimble is available from Zesty Technology.

title: Dew shield for SkyWatcher 9x50 finder scope

description.text:
Warning a single wall is a bit thin and quite fragile, I will probably prepare and test a version with a thickness of at least 1mm.

Dew shield for the SkyWatcher 9x50 finder scope, that has a 57.4mm outer diameter.

EDIT : New THICK version with 2mm walls as the original design is prone to delamination

Length is 200mm.

I've printed it with 0.3mm layer height, and resized it to 101% in Cura before print, it slides smoothly on the scope.

It could be used on any other 50mm finders by just increasing the XY scale accordingly to the external diameter of your specific scope.

For minimal internal reflection, try to get it the mattest you can, by chosing a specific PLA or lowering the print temperature.
MatteForge black filament gives great results (see pictures).

If printed with usual PLA, it could be a good idea to flock the interior with some adhesive black felt for visual use.

Time lapse : https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=nbW69UtOXfo

description.text:
I've been using the Quick Fit X carriage by Yurykk for a few months now, and it works great, but it has a few issues in my particular setup. The belt clamp position were too close to the back of the motor by 5mm, there was not sufficient clearance without modification to remove a budaschnozzle 1.2 equipped extruder, and there was a small amount of flex in the entire carriage. I have attempted to rectify those issues. This carriage has slightly more mass than the origional, and is designed to require heat set inserts for the rear bearing mounts and the fan / accessory mount under the platform. I was going to try and make a 3 point carriage, but the hole for the extruder hot end is just too big to be able to get a good offset for the front bearing in the event of a single bearing, so I left it at 4 bearings. I did space the rear bearings out a bit since the room was already there.   
Way experemental, i'll print one and see how it works here shortly  
Noticed I managed to draw the conversion backwards from how I need the latch on my machine, so here's an identical, but mirrored STL as well. The other one printed fine, will upload pictures later.

Print it out, then insert M3 heat set inserts at the appropriate locations for the back bearings, belt mount points and the accessory mount up front. You will need the same 605 bearing and hardware for the latch as you would for Yurykk's variant.

I Remixed the Z-axis group JetGuy Barry uses in his Core XY Cube which is for use in a 2020 aluminium extrusion frame type machine in such a way that it can be used in a (wooden) box type machine like the SmartRapCore printers.

comments.text:
Indeed this print is not easy, and I found it to be very slicer sensitive. I sliced it with Cura, 1 mm shell thickness, 0.06 and 0.09 mm layer height at various infill levels and all of them printed well. When I sliced it with Slic3r, it would always ruin the print, mainly because of the known "spiking" issue.
The one in the picture is printed at 0.09mm, 1mm shell, 50% infill with full cooling and the minimum layer time set to 30 seconds. No support used, but I used a 10mm brim to ensure a good adhesion to the heated bed. Make sure not to print it too fast as it's very thin walled in the top. Which issues to you encounter during printing?

description.text:
See the pdf file for a more detailed description. This is a design for a clamp to be used to attach accessories to 1-inch T-Slot extruded rails (80/20 extrusion, profile 1010). Included is a complete design for an LED lamp on a gooseneck which utilizes the clamp and can be quickly attached to or repositioned on a T-Slot extrusion. The intention is for this to provide a design that can be adapted to your own needs; Solidworks and Sketchup source files are included in the uploaded files.

This design relies on gluing the clamps to a box for the lamp, and for this ABS was used. An excellent glue for ABS can be made by dissolving bits of ABS filament in acetone to make a thin paste. I've not found any suitable adhesive for PLA to create a strong joint, and so this design should be printed in ABS, or the design modified for some other attach method.

Revision 9/28/2017: Added a chamfer on the cutout for the power connector, as the panel thickness is just a little too large for the switch to properly snap into place securely. Files affected: box.stl, box.factory, lamp.sldprt. I did not update lamp.skp with the chamfered cutout.

Notes:

See the pdf file for further comments on the print parameters and particularly the infill setting. Simplify3D factory files are included in the uploaded files.

For the spring to work properly, the clamp must be printed flat on the bed as shown in the STL file. See the pdf file for more info about spring design and modification.
Some light sanding will be needed to get a proper fit to the t-slot rail so that the assembly will slide on the rail. A fingernail file works well for this.

This was designed in Solidworks and the STL files were then imported into Sketchup and simplified to create the Sketchup source files.

Solidworks facilitated a tricky part of the design, which is to get the spring design so that it is preloaded and applying tension with the t-slot channel tabs in the proper place. This required that the part be printed with the clamp arm rotated so that there would be tension when used. So the spring when printed had to be wound up, but still function when bent into the operating position. Solidworks can make two curve lengths equal, so I made a reference spring profile for the spring applied to the rail, and then rotated the moving arm on the clamp into print position while maintaining the same curve length on the spring. This assured that when the spring was operated, the tabs would line up properly.

I could not find the same "make curve lengths equal" constraint capability in OnShape.

Rectangular profile sweep using a sketch on the axis of the vase as path, and used the rotating sweep and specified 180°.
Did another sweep with the same inputs, only opposite rotation.

Revolved a boss using the inner surface, and made sure to not merge result.

Shelled that revolve. Copied the inner surface of the revolve.

Surface cut the outside of the ribs, and then circular pattern the bodies until there were enough ribs.

Combined them all together, then used the inner surface shell copy to cut the residual ribs.

description.text:
This is a design for a basic pinhole camera. Further modification will be necessary to function, as explained in the Instructions. This design is loosely based upon the following three resources: http://www.kodak.com/global/en/consumer/education/lessonPlans/pinholeCamera/pinholeCanBox.shtml http://www.matchboxpinhole.com/ http://www.mrpinhole.com/ If you have any ideas or comments, be sure to post them, but remember to be nice!
Pinhole Camera Design by Connor Hollenback is licensed under a Creative Commons Attribution-Share Alike 3.0 United States License.
Permissions beyond the scope of this license may be available at http://nouseforadventures.blogspot.com/.

Before you do anything, paint the entire thing matte black.
Much of these instructions are very similar to the ones on http://www.matchboxpinhole.com/ so go there if you are having trouble. I haven\'t finished developing a good method for advancing the film, but I am working on it, and will post updates here when I figure everything out. I am also working on a shutter mechanism, but you can just use the shutter on http://www.matchboxpinhole.com/ The Film Carrier:
The small rectangle gets screwed on to the medium sized rectangle at each of the four corners. In between the top and bottom components there should be very thin spacers at each of the screws, to give the film space to slide between them. That then gets screwed on to the inside of the body using the same four screws. Drill some pilot holes before you start, and then using slightly bigger screws than the pilot holes, carefully screw them in. then put some nuts on the end of the screws to prevent slipping. These should be machine screws, by the way. The Pinhole:
For this step, you will need an aluminum soda can, a sewing pin, and some electrical tape.
First, clean the soda can, then (carefully!!) cut out a small square of aluminum, and, following the instructions at http://www.matchboxpinhole.com/ make a 0.5mm hole in the middle of the aluminum, then tape it to the inside (or outside) of the large rectangle component (labeled \"Pinhole_Body_2\"), so that the hole is directly in the middle of the rectangular gap in the middle of the component. Putting It Together:
For this part, use two small cabinet draw clasps, and two small hinges. They can be found at any hardware store. Also get some foam tape to help seal off the enclosure from any light.
First cut the foam tape to the correct size, and put it on the top edge of \"Pinhole_Body_1\". Make sure that there are no gaps, or else there will be light leaks, unless you like light leaks, in which case, just leave them.
Then you can mount the hinges and clasps on opposite sides of each other, making sure that the large rectangle fits snuggly on top of the body. I'll be making a wooden model soon, as I don\'t have a 3 axis CNC :( so hopefully I can post some more images and clear up any rough points in the design.

description.text:
This zero model is intended for young children to make sense of mathematical ideas involving negative numbers. The essential idea is that every number has an additive inverse so that (+A) + (-A) =0. For example, (+1) + (-1) = 0 and (+5) + (-5) = 0. This big idea, together with the connections between addition and subtraction, can be used to explain why 0 – (-1)= +1, and eventually why (-1)(-1) = +1. It is really a fun perspective and has healthy implications for higher mathematics. And, yes, subtraction can be interpreted as “take away.” Thus, 0 – (-1) means taking (-1) from 0. Well, 0 is “(+1)+(-1)”, thus, the result is (+1).

description.text:
I've owned my pagoda antenna for a while now and have liked everything about it besides its strength. It's so easy to get the 3 plates bent out of shape! I've tried nearly every other 3D printed pagoda cap/protector on Thingiverse but they all either fall off easily or just don't protect the antenna. That is why I designed this super durable, super simple pagoda antenna protector. It consists of two sets of spacers and an upper TPU cap. the spacers ensure that each plate remains perfectly spaced at all times. The upper TPU cap ensures that the spacers don't fall out and that the upper plate doesn't get scratched or chipped in the event of a hard crash. The bottom spacers are held securely in place by a tube of heat shrink.

Note that this is only compatible with the 5.8ghz version of the pagoda antenna as the others have different plate spacing.

title: Functional Attack on Titan Sword V2 (read description before printing!)

description.text:
This is my own design of a life-size Attack on Titan sword replica. The blade is detachable and is steadily held by a magnet lock. I'm quite satisfied with this one personally, but I find that there is still room for improvement, so this will most definately not be my last version.

PRINTER'S NOTES: scale everything down uniformly to approximately 90% (give or take a couple percent if you have bigger/smaller than average hands). In order to make one, you need to print five of the Blade mid.STL and one of all the other files. In addition to the 3D-printed parts, you will need a 4x785mm threaded steel rod (the blade core), a 4x36mm (threaded) rod (the lever axle), and two 5x5mm neodymium disc magnets (like these https://www.supermagnete.nl/eng/disc-magnets-neodymium/disc-magnet-diameter-5mm-height-5mm-neodymium-n45-nickel-plated_S-05-05-N).

Do note that if you scale it to anything else than 90%, the metal parts will not fit perfectly.

Assemble the blade by screwing the middle blade segments from the male connecting side to the female connecting side onto the blade core, followed by the blade base, and lastly slide and glue the blade top on the other end.

Assemble the grip by installing one of the magnets into the magnet pocket of either of the grip halves (as indicated with red on the second image), before glueing the two grip halves together. Install the other magnet in the magnet pocket of the blocker (as indicated with red on the third image), such that both magnets have identical poles facing outwards (they need repulse eachother). Then slide the blocker into the blocker slot with the thin side facing the blade slot, before installing the lever.

If the magnet lock does not work smoothly, try sanding the contact surfaces of the moving parts.
